Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law introducing administrative liability for violating the time and manner of payment for goods (work, services) in procurement for State and municipal needs.
The Act is intended to address the very acute problem of the failure of customers to comply with their obligations in public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, it was common for entrepreneurs to be unable to obtain payment under public and municipal contracts already executed.
At the same time, the President of the Russian Federation instructed the Procurator-General of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not deal with the unfair customers who had entered into unfunded contracts, tried to evade their payment obligations and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in general in the country.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office has submitted 9,700 submissions, disciplinary proceedings have been brought against 4,500 officials, administrative proceedings have been instituted against 533 officials, and 75 cases have been submitted to investigative bodies for the purpose of conducting procedural checks, of which 46 have been prosecuted.
As a result, over 66 billion roubles were paid to entrepreneurs.
These huge amounts were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion-dollar contracts.
Unsound debts have been caused by numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs by far more modest amounts.
Here's a special case.
The head of a small company won a multi-million ruble social transport service contest.
The man invested all his working capital, fully discharged his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is an increasing financial pool of debts on wages, taxes and loans that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought assistance from the Public Prosecutor's Office.
The problem has now been minimized in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt on State and municipal contracts identified by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the Office of the Public Prosecutor operates under a manual crisis management regime.
The Attorney-General conducts face-to-face meetings with local authorities, where all violations discovered by prosecutors are dealt with in a substantive manner and measures are taken to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Act No. 189-FZ amending the Code of Administrative Offences to establish the administrative liability of the officials of the customer for violating the time and procedure for paying for goods (work, services) in procurement to meet State and municipal needs, signed last week by the President of the Russian Federation, will be a qualitative improvement in the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was drafted by the Ministry of Development of Russia on the initiative of the Office of the Procurator-General.
The new law would add an article to the Code of Administrative Offences, which provided for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 roubles for the violation by an official of the employer of the time limit and procedure for paying for goods, works and services in public and municipal procurement.
If an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he or she will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are applied in practice.
