Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28 per cent of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by the Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a highland province about the size of New Jersey, where 153,000 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced around $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua can boast of forest reserves valued at $78 billion.
These wealths, however, entail one misfortune for the Pahuas, guaranteeing that Indonesia's powerful armed forces retain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by The New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy by the Pahuas threaten the existence of this golden vein and are mercilessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuas have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, massacres in the high-lying indigenous peoples of Papua in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything”, a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane contains evidence of atrocities committed the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture – particularly frequent, as stated in another report, rape and electrocution – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because incidents occur every week," says Andreas Harsono, researching in Indonesia for "Human Rights Watch".
The nuts have been prolonged as Papua's resources have attracted the influx of displaced persons from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5-millione population is 83 percent Christian, but the demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands – Java, Sumatra, and Sulawesi.
Javan shops, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to withstand competition.
"Migrants began selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market at a cheaper price than Papua Natives," explains Abet Yo, a twenty-four-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, due to work.
"Because of this, the indigenous Papuan mother (woman) Papuan people lost their market".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, known in the people as Jokovi, vowed to address inequality and violations of rights in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, a former carpenter secured support from 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But there has been little change in Papua, and locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokovi, expecting him to fulfil our hopes for justice," says Yo.
In fact, just two months after the inauguration of Jokovi Paniai in October, the tragedy survived.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing Christmas hymns at the bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle burst out of the dark.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one soldier resented their tone and returned with four soldiers some time later.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased the children and hit them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Yemo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election building, and the next day the situation worsened.
About a thousand Pahuasian men, women and children gathered in a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the White, a dance of the Papuas tribe of me pago: running in circles and depicting bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, soldiers were ordered by internal radio to "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," as it was said in an official document seen by the correspondents of TIME magazine but which was not published in the local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayamé, head of Kego Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to disperse.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, a bullet suddenly hit my left wrist," he told the magazine "TIME", standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayama still doesn't know who shot, but says the bullet came from the sherry of the assembled soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were many shots," he adds.
A local resident of Alfius Yowa was hit three times, as his cousin told him, who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," he grimly told the magazine "TIME" Johanes, who, like many Indonesians, only uses one name.
"I saw him dead... I kissed him".
General Yotje Mende, Papua Police Chief Inspector, told reporters that his officers were only "protecting" their base because she was under attack.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," said Papua Commissioner Pujo Sulistiyo, a police spokesman in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and much more injured.
The murder news didn't get to Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, in which he expressed condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuse of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately, the excuses came out.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the nineties or in the early zeros.
The point is, we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be done," he said.
Viranto then retracted his words, speaking with the magazine "TIME" on June 5, in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through a court of law.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the death of more than 1,000 people during the bloody East Timor independence vote in 1999, said that 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai met with such statements with a dark mistrust.
"I have been questioned four times over the last three years, but there has been no change at all," Johanes says.
"I'm tired".
