In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that, by drastically changing the course of the ozone standards, he simply fulfilled the EPA's obligation to work with the states in an integrated process of timely implementation of the new standards.
"Under previous EPA administrations, it was often impossible to meet the target dates, then waited for claims from groups of activists and others and discussed the time frames during the settlement of the case," Pruitt said, who filed more than a dozen claims against EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through litigation, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our statutes and the authority that he confers upon us."
However, the EPA statement states that Pruitt may, at some point, use his "authority to delay and other statutory powers" again to ensure that the "jcyjdfys" rules are clear-cut and on all available information.
