The 1948 Ford Mercury drove past spectators in Monroe village in Georgia and rushed with a roar to the small Morse Ford Bridge.
When the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, came to the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked her way.
The main one, a middle-aged man in a suit in a thin strip, pulled a cigar and looked through the windshield.
Sitting inside shivered for fear.
"We need that nigga, Roger!" a man squirted.
"Get him out of the car!"
The piercing cries broke the silence when a young black man was pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene that took place on July 22 is just a mocking.
But when Roger's neck was slammed with a loop, almost all the viewers really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to replay the night that the Cooksklanians lynched two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey in 1946.
No one was convicted of these murders.
"It's amazing that no man has been arrested in all these years - although we see them beside us; although we know who they are," Tyrone Brooks says, who helped organize the production.
"It's a stain on our story and it's a stone on our souls."
The 71-year-old Brooks is a former member of the Congress of Georgia who has spent his entire life fighting for human rights.
To him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to Monroe residents that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want investigation, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We can't go to healing and reconciliation until we get justice."
The Coroner covers the sheet body of one of the victims of the lynching at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI material received by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights defenders say that the city has always been well aware of two related motives of vigilantes: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ruling allowed black citizens for the first time to vote on the primary, which was to take place that summer.
Around the same election, the FBI reports that black exploiter Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, with a woman in a fight.
Brooks says that according to rumours around town, Hester was sleeping with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the child she was supposed to have was not from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Loi Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 in bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove out of prison and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that he organized and commanded Harrison's murders," that's the conclusion in an FBI report.
"It is also clear that there was a conspiracy between state and city law enforcement agencies that not only took part in the murders, but also destroyed evidence and concealed witnesses' identities."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt on voting rights," he says.
"They were all killed to send a signal to blacks in town: if you register and vote, you'll be the same."
For almost a decade, Cassandra Greene has been running an annual play reproducing that lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visible, he captures the audience and tells of the deep racism that many would like to think is no longer in America.
It's hard to look at and even harder to turn around, but Green thinks that's what matters.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch's courts because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
The rehearsals of this year began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - gathered in the room and listened to a slit-down view of the play over the years.
Wade Marbo was the director with Green.
He has played the role of chief member of the clan for several years, but says the role has never been made easier.
"I think I'm dirty because it's not the man I am," Marbo says.
"But I think it's very important to remember this story because we don't want to go back at the time."
In the room, actors Darius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
Spectal begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Screams Rascon back.
There's a blow.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all the black actors) is hoisted.
Green laughs loudest.
"What's up," asks Ascon.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I overplaying?
"No," says Green through laughter.
"I just don't think the whites used to say 'nigg'."
"Yes, yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You have to pronounce solid 'r'".
And there's also a change in the energy in the room: the discomfort is replaced by a sense of partnership.
Everything must be done right, not only for the play, but also for the memory of the four people killed.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Rascona says the word "n", it's clear and sharp.
No man laughs.
The show ends cruelly and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of actors and performs Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
A hundred yards away, half the audience wipes out tears and sweat.
There are almost equal numbers of black and white viewers.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to watch the performance; many live close by.
They all endured Georgia's heavy perfume for almost eight hours while Brooks took them on a pilgrimage to Malcolm and Dorsey's graves.
Until then, the murders remained only a story, but now that they are standing in the same place where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are floating in the air.
When the last note of the song closes, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend to their heads, touch blood paint, and still bodies, and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead," one little boy mumbles like he's reminding himself of that.
In a few minutes, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly it's over.
Actors drop ropes off their necks and wipe out tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, a man in a suit who played the main puppet.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional burden of the play finally hit him.
"It's all right," one of the women whispers.
"We know your heart is good.
You had a reason for that."
Later, the audience sits down for dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta livelyly discuss the performance with the black couple they just met.
Denisa Daplinski has difficulty finding words to describe how she feels after the play.
"It's hard to listen to these horrible, horrible words, and actions... people who look like you, and who do it because they look like you," she says.
"After that, I think lynchings are still happening," she adds, "only now it's called the police shooting."
In the other corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks, who remembers his work as a human rights defender, gained general attention.
He says he's already started planning next year's performance.
"The production inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we have experienced, but also teaches us," he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this lesson, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, those who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it."
