New results of tests to assess the age of asylum-seekers in Sweden were published
Recent results of tests of asylum-seekers in Sweden subjected to a new method of medical age assessment show that more than 80 per cent of those tested were assessed as persons over 18 years of age, but not all trust in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) began conducting tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make an age estimate in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, Migriationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensics agency has now published 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of the testees were rated as 18 years or older, and in another 25 cases the forensics agency estimated that the test was "probably 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "probably under 18".
Tests are conducted only when the age of the person is in doubt.
According to Johan Gouranceon of the forensics agency, the results match those of the past months.
"We don't see a big difference in statistics over the past months, numbers are quite relevant," he said to the portal "The Local".
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published 581 test results and reported that in 442 cases "most likely, the age of the test is 18 years or more."
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, a person had openly stated that 18 was being fulfilled this year.
The method of conducting a medical assessment of age, which is to X-ray the teeth of wisdom and to scan the knee joints and give them to dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Claude Marcus Institute of Carolina, whose work is to assess the biological maturity of humans to determine whether they went through puberty before or after normal.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think I should use the measurement techniques that are being used now.
The biological age is thus very inaccurate.
If we can't define him with confidence, we shouldn't pretend we can," he said to Metro.
However, Göranssen of the forensics agency spoke in favour of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of mistaking a child as an adult is small.
We face the greatest risk when a man is about 18, in which case he is about 10 per cent."
