The President will determine the manner and location of the oath.
Where and how new Russian citizens will pledge allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have been drawn up by the State Committee on Legislation and State Building.
As early as a week ago, MPs planned to directly define the oath of office in the law.
Children under the age of 18 and those incompetent will be exempted from taking a solemn oath, as follows from the revised text of the amendments to the draft law on citizenship of the Russian Federation (as it is in the possession of the News), which the committee will consider on 11 July before its second reading at its meeting.
On 6 June, President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of swearing in on the Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents during a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The members of the Parliament have adopted this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the revocation of the decision to grant citizenship to those who have subsequently been convicted of a number of terrorist or extremist offences: for example, public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (article 205.2, paragraph 2, of the Criminal Code), as well as for the hijacking of an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if the act is linked to terrorism (article 211, paragraph 4, of the Criminal Code).
According to the bill, his logic was this: in issuing citizenship documents, a person subscribes to a promise to abide by Russian law - by embarking on the path of extremism, he violates that promise.
In April, the bill was introduced in the State Duma by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev (Uniform Russia), Gennady Züganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Justly Russia) and the Speaker of DG Viacheslav Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies accepted it on first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Building and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but it has now been reworked.
It now states that the President of the Russian Federation will establish the order of the oath.
Previously, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the Citizenship Act of the Russian Federation, stating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the State coat of arms and the Russian flag in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place, a list of places where the coat of arms of the Russian Federation could be placed, is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include the courts, the offices of the heads of State of the constituent entities, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, the heads of the federal executive, etc.
Most likely, it could also be a registry.
A solemn oath will be issued to those who wish to acquire Russian citizenship after officials have checked their documents.
But the Russian passport will be obtained only after the person has sworn in, and follows from the finalized text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text stated that Russia would be sworn in from the age of 18 rather than the age of 14.
The rule that would exempt persons with disabilities or limited legal capacity, as well as those who could not pronounce, read or sign the oath themselves, had been retained.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt “other persons” from this procedure.
The updated bill also lays down a special procedure for the admission to Russian citizens of Ukraine who are considered Russian speakers.
They will have to formally renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a declaration to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application would need to be handed over to Russian officials.
A waiver of “foreign” nationality will not be required, as it is now, if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible “for reasons beyond the individual's control”.
A corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among whom the first vice-speaker, DG Ivan Melnikov (PRPF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all “Uniform Russia”).
I think a lot of you know it's unrealistic to get a certificate from Ukraine, but it's just impossible.
