Judges are offered protection from presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (CHR), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes that the powers of the presidents of the courts be limited and that their election be introduced.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts which will not be tied to the administrative division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals under the Presidential Instruction.
HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the council.
At a meeting with the council on 8 December 2016, some cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as well as problems of public scrutiny in places of detention (see IO of 9 December).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals that deal both with the independence of the judiciary and the detection of judicial errors and with the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlev human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the post of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judiciary, the HRC is of the view that the president of the court should submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed that the President be deprived of the right to allocate cases to judges.
It's open to experts, it can be a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled to “predicate the results of the judge's qualification, initiate disciplinary proceedings against him or her, and decide on additional material payments”.
In doing so, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move towards “the election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and to “invigorate their powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation”.
All the presidents of the courts (from the Republic to the District) are now appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes to re-organize appeals and cassation in the ordinary courts.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative and territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that “the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation should be ensured, not at the level of the regional judicial authorities in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts”.
The experts are based on the practice of arbitral tribunals.
They have “judicial districts” which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials who are hampered by the use of “telephone law”.
HRC Justices of the Peace propose that the people's assessors strengthen their involvement in certain “classes of civil and administrative cases”.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honour and dignity, deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"It's just our proposals," explained "I'm a member of the HRC, a retired Constitutional Court judge, Tamara Morchkov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate related not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time before the armed forces (among the co-authors, the Office of the Attorney-General and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) can carry out their mission.
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the president of the armed forces, Vyacheslav Lebedev, is due before 1 September.
Living a high life: semi-story and crafty designer techniques turned this small apartment into an Earls Court apartment into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former real-estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a pretty model Queen Anne-style house, and in favor of a new design says Joan didn't pack her things and move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger square," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were just as high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered the price the same day."
Since the first look, a 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally, it was an apartment with one bedroom complex layout – to get into the bedroom, it had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and semi-storey to squeeze the maximum benefit out of the generous ceiling height.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
These were my demands," she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill architectural and design studio, Duck & Shed, to use ceilings of 12.5 feet high and create a dwelling that would not only be a successful project, but would be Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-storey where you could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the brift.
"Work with steel structures is very complex," he explains.
"We had to place the premises so that they were one above the other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they would be at the right height and allow the rooms to be used from above and below."
This decision allowed Erfan to set up two full-size rooms one over the other in space – and many more interesting.
From the semi-story through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" opens a view of the gorgeous living room below.
Mirror furniture with gold finish, silver accents, and vintage lighting devices from Serge Muy set the design style.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, width, and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror shield appears to be a window in the other room.
At the entrance, mirror cupboards are used to store Joan's entire dish.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block itself in the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new about the kitchens that are coming up.
The unique thing about this kitchen is that it's a moving door up like a garage.
"This was where engineering art was involved," Erfan tells of the reinforced steel-based fibreboard door.
"It has a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily".
Due to the prudent use of space and storage facilities, Joan received an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom, and improved layout.
"In the end, floor space is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your real estate is valued by," Erfan says.
"Deadly speaking, a real estate agent will enter and calculate based on floor space".
Here, they were able to increase the area of the sexes by using quality materials that provide a shade of luxury.
"Motherals are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the house," Erfan says.
"Nobody falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't hurt the strings of our hearts."
