Paul has wanted out of the family business since 2014, but in the Supreme Court there is still a fierce dispute over the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother, Anna's brothers own 87 properties worth over half a billion dollars bought since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's property list today includes office buildings, development plots in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Bank and Mount Buller, and shopping centers in suburbs.
By agreement with Colin's late father, who Paul describes as the "major driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family, he owns about two thirds of the company's assets and Paul has about one third.
According to the court, this means Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's property is 176 million.
The division of property and money became Paul's stumbling block.
"The section offered by Colin gives him, in my view, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed attempts at reconciliation, the first Supreme Court hearings were held.
The brothers are now debating who will control the existing business, from which Paul believes Colin has excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but blames Paul for the incompetent management of some objects.
In the testimony Colin gave at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider the family a top priority," he wrote.
Court costs are rising as a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, e-mails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer are included in the case; both sides have engaged the most prominent lawyers, including King Allan Myers, and the best cooks.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s they have run dairy bars and gastronoms, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood that opened Colin's first family jeans store.
Colin says he launched Westco when he was "in the last grade of school, and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years)".
Anna De Lutis says that he and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to hand over their property to their sons without conflict.
"Louigi often told me he didn't want the brothers to know in court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, no longer belong to the De Lutis group; Colina says Mark received $10 million when he left the business and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "dissatisfied with the financial conditions of their office."
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to the 2015 biography of Eddie McGir, the best friend of the television star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied with a text message saying that since the case had not yet been tried, "I really have nothing to say."
"I'm very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and talk in court the name of our family," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a statement that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see Paul and I arguing in court," he said, adding, "still hoping to resolve the conflict."
On Friday, that hope seemed to have dissipated.
"A judgment on our case will soon be handed down by the court," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really do it.
