"At a meeting held by the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly with staff management on his first working day, he identified the main problem at the White House under President Donald Trump, which he hopes to solve: poor channels of information to the president".
Kelly told the staff that the information should go through it - in paper form or through briefings - because the president would be better at making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is perfectly correct, but others have already failed in trying to control Trump by tracking the information to him.
President Trump's relationship with television began decades ago - and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching television is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, was outraged by unfair campaign coverage, it was useful to demonstrate to him that he had received fair coverage in publications that could be persuaded," said "Politico" Sam Nanberg, a former electoral staff adviser in February.
Tara Palmeri then wrote in Politico that "according to six former members of the election staff, to keep Trump's Twitter habit under control, you had to make sure that there was a constant stream of praise in the personal information he received."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habit was ever "under control" is ridiculous.
Maybe these members of the election staff know something we don't know, for example, that if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about tweets Trump hasn't published.
If his staff saved him at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has always been able to keep Trump from pouring oil into the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people constantly try to advance their summons by providing Trump with material - reliable or not - that confirms their views.
"Politico" - just to this story - wrote in May about the tendency of councillors to constantly give the president questionable information.
Consider one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Trump's current and former employees say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This was the case in late February, when someone slipped to the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, an Internet provocator website of Charles C. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Welsh was accused of being "standing behind a number of leaks" in the White House.
It doesn't matter that Johnson's been tweeted forever for aggressive behavior, that he didn't present specific facts, or that in the past he'd run false charges and then drop them.
Trump read the article and began to ask staff about Welsh."
Goldmacher adds that then head of staff Raines Pribus and staff secretary Rob Porter "tryed to build a system to control and document the flow of paper that Trump receives."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same thing.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Pribus, but Trump still has impulsive nature, and his aides continue to fight each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
The Tumen Public Prosecutor's Office is fighting against an HIV-dissociated woman
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office challenged the ruling of the Kalininsky Rayud of Tumeni, who had dropped the criminal case against a local resident whose HIV-related death had been caused by a young daughter.
The child is said to have died because the mother is HIV-dissociated and refused treatment.
However, the court relieved her of responsibility in connection with her reconciliation with the father.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office believes that the crime cannot be allowed to go unpunished without setting a precedent for other HIV-dissidents.
The case against a woman resident of Tumeni was instituted under article 109, paragraph 1, of the Criminal Code (a cause of death by negligence) in April, after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"Woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection did not exist," explained the Prosecutor's Office of Tumen Oblast.
The criminal case went to the Kalininsky Rayud of Tumeni, who decided on 25 July to terminate it.
The request was made by the deceased girl's father, explaining that he had "simplified his wife, had no claim against her, she made amends and apologized."
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office did not accept the court ' s decision and filed an appeal, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be quashed and referred to a new hearing.
The girl died, and it's impossible to make up for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-positive mother refused to examine the baby and treat her with a dangerous infection, despite the doctors' advice," reported to the prosecution's press service.
In the view of the supervisory authority, it should be punished, otherwise other HIV-dissidents would follow suit.
As reported at the Tumen AIDS Centre, some 12 children living with HIV in the Tyumensk region now receive no medical care because of parents' refusal.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of the special group's work, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV changed their mind - they allowed them to diagnose, they started taking medication," said Elena Losev, a spokesman for the AIDS Centre.
She said that parents could not be legally affected and that not all HIV-infected children could be found - mothers were prevented from examining them, hiding themselves and running away from hospitals.
The risk of HIV-dissidence
At the end of last year, Peterburg sociologists presented the results of the first study of the so-called HIV-dissident movement in Russia.
HIV-dissidents refer to people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Medics and AIDS service activists in the NDA call such views anti-medical and view their distribution as a serious threat.
