Italy is tightening the tone for ships of NGOs rescuing migrants.
Italy warned NGOs that owned rescue vessels in the Mediterranean Sea that they would not be able to continue their work unless they complied with the new regulations governing their activities.
"If NGOs fail to comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," said Interior Minister Mario Minnity in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
Minnity's warning came the day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew actually cooperated with traffickers and facilitated illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had been working for only one year, refused to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Cartosio.
"For us, the salvation of human life is and will remain a top priority, so we very much regret that we cannot now continue to operate in the search and rescue zone," states the organization's statement on social media.
"We can assess all the charges now made only after we gather all the information and assess the situation."
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventa vessel belonging to the Jugend Rettet since October.
His crew is suspected of receiving migrants on board by entire lifeboats, who were sent directly to them by traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place only 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, as stated in the charges, the contents of which were published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in this zone, rather from humanitarian zeal than from any other motive.
The Code of Conduct assumes mainly that the Yuvent vessels will have on board an Italian police officer who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the Code: Save the Children, Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open embraces from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new regulations unnecessary but acceptable, provided that they did not involve any “significant change or interference” in its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minnity said that the sharp decline in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations in recent weeks indicates that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In the last few days we started to see the light at the end of the tunnel," said the minister.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with the Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any party to the conflict"
The Russian Federation authorities have recently increased their policy markedly on the Libyan track, and visits to Moscow have involved delegations of the opposing Libyan parties.
The head of the Russian Contact Group on Intra-Livian Settlement under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, the Assistant Head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Deng, told "I" what Moscow's goals are in this region and on whom he is betting.
The contact group on Libya, which you are chairing, is hardly known.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine knows about it.
And here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The Contact Group was established at the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Her activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya.
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The beginning of the group was the arrest in Libya of a Russian tanker, the Mechanic Cebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board.
We've been thinking about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, was established, and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How come you're the one who led it?
As I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the work of the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanic.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict, and with Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government is based, led by Faiz Saraj. - IA) and Tobruk (a parliament that opposes the Government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls eastern Libya. - IA).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya, IA), we were able to quickly negotiate the release of Russian sailors.
It was then agreed to establish a contact group to make better use of those contacts.
Its task is to analyse the situation, identify key factors and players, and engage in dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I wish to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to associate ourselves with any of the parties to the conflict; we are engaged in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group, and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
The contact group is now composed of five persons.
They include people with experience in the security forces, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also wish to include in the team of regional specialists, representatives of the RA Institute of the Middle East.
No one of our staff is permanently in Libya, and that is not necessary.
Are there Russian military advisers, trainers in Libya now?
And if so, which side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group is a former military member...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
Like when we visit hot spots.
Or such closed cities for us as Misurata (where militia groups are based, who played a role in overthrowing Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and have increased markedly in the following years.
We arrived in Misurata in January of this year.
We were scared, they said it was all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess for ourselves the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who was responsible for what, why rumours such as what the real role of Islamists was.
In Misurat, we met with all the representatives of the units that were engaged in the destruction of the IG in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was repulsed from militants of the banned Islamic State in Russia, IU).
We wanted to look at them, to meet these people, to check out the information that they were the ones who were the key to the destruction of the IH in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these services to himself.
And what conclusion did you come to?
The "Islamic State" in Libya didn't defeat Haftar?
He didn't do it.
Haftar performed operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And the IG in Sirte was fought by structures subordinate to the Government in Tripoli.
And by the way, we've invited to Russia the people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation.
And they came -- the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, and the Libyan delegation was received by the Federation Council, the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Rosg Guard.
You, as we understand it, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the sentiments of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections that were reached in Paris at the end of July by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or, again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, agreements will be thwarted, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to take power alone?
For us, the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting was a good signal, not so long ago, that was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders were very negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misurat, and Haftar was on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that very day.
It was a coincidence.
But they didn't believe in coincidence in Misurat.
We were told, "You must be a very brave man to come to us today."
But our task is precisely to show: we do not support only Haftar, we are engaged in dialogue with all key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar have been in touch.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR make it easier to understand with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, he's very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us makes it easier to have a dialogue with him, of course.
And by the way, it's not just him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misurat, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And here they are speaking Russian very well.
And stretching towards Russia, feeling a little nostalgia about it.
Do you consider it likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya would be lifted as soon as possible?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in supplying Russian weapons?
Of course they are, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict, nor do we want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like to see all of them in about equal positions.
With regard to the arms embargo, Libyans have constantly called for Russia to help lift it.
The constitution-making process in Libya is now well under way.
We hope that the parties will come to compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then there must be an election, which was also mentioned at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and legitimate power is finally elected (and none of the parties now has such status), the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the United Nations.
It is pointless and dangerous to raise this issue now; it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
There was news in the media the other day that Italy, faced with African refugees sailing from Libya, felt abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is it that Haftar troops will control the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
Italians need Russia's support because Moscow has a dialogue with both Haftar and Saraj and Misurata and the south of the country.
Tribes in southern Libya play a major role in this matter, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Are we talking about the southerners stopping the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
So, by implication, you were turning back the buses that Nigerian migrants ride?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite southerners in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see a consensus on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The Head of Government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered to be an Islamist who is a supporter of the establishment of sharia law in the country.
How radical is he?
Would that not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I'll give him my personal opinion.
In my view, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya must be an entirely normal country, a moderately Islamic, open world.
And he is also active in the fight against terrorists.
How could he have such a reputation?
It has been created by countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislature, the executive and the judiciary are located.
There's a national oil corporation, a national bank, and other government entities.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
And we mixed all the cards with them, and we started to communicate actively with both Tripoli and Tobruck.
We are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with the Libyan State oil company, the NOC.
The NOC director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosnefti Igor Sechin made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with her?
I suppose I'll resell it.
What other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
Plans to re-sign contracts under Muammar Gaddafi.
These include, inter alia, previous transport arrangements (rail construction), energy (electricity) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, as in the case of Iran, is the oil-for-service scheme?
I don't know what the plan is, I don't deal directly with these issues.
In fact, Russia’s economy is not the main one in Libya.
We're actually doing peacekeeping work there.
For us, the most important thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya is no longer a propitious environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, that is the main task — to help the Libyan people and to push terrorists out of there.
Do you have any evidence of the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that, to date, none of the Russians and other countries of the former USSR were there.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya, IA) and no Russian speech.
Which state are these fighters from?
I wouldn't want to go into those details.
Then we'll put it another way.
How many of the Islamic militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are almost no Libyans, not more than 5% of them.
The others are from here.
Could Moscow hold intra-Livian talks like Paris?
There are plans.
We have been actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have indicated their willingness to come back to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits are yet to take place, and I hope that the timing and venue of the talks will be clarified.
