Michelle Carter's sentence for reports that prompted Conrad Roy's suicide
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for having used text messages and telephone calls to induce her boyfriend Conrad Roy's suicide.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence in prison and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on 13 July 2014.
Roy's father said at the Thursday hearing, "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until the appeal.
She was at risk of a maximum of 20 years, but her lawyers stated that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing by, squeezing her hands and putting her eyes down.
"By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," said the prosecutor to the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her.
She didn't admit responsibility," she said.
"She has shown no remorse".
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "tragic case she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that in his view her "age, maturity or even mental illness did not have a noticeable impact on her actions".
The Prosecutor read out statements from Roy Lynn Roy's mother saying, "Not a day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I handle it - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever," he says.
Roy's sister Kamdin Roy said that she was relentlessly haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"The man who's always been with me since I was born is the pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would make it a crime to advise a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident caught the attention of the entire country when it was revealed that he had been prompted to commit suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know how many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she killed herself, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad," and, "You just need to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted attention through Roy's death, and prohibited her from talking to the press to prevent her getting what she wanted.
The views of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of killing her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
30-year-old Knox published her dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which stated, "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
