Astronomers found a hell of a planet where even iron can melt.
Having first studied the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, the astrophysics were greatly surprised by its temperature, which is able to evaporate iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so warmed up by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
Hubble's telescope captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature makes the water in the planet's atmosphere glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to so-called "hot Jupiter" - gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet of the solar system, but located dozens of times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, the exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "terrestrial" days, and its gas casing is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and South France, but it is now feared that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavanda has grown worse due to arid weather and disease-borne insects; this has caused the constant headache of scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert from the Provence-based Agricultural Research Institute CRIEPPAM, says, "Lavanda in Provence is indeed at risk because in recent years this plant has experienced the effects of climate change: in the spring, and especially in the autumn, the rains have become much smaller.
This affects the life span of the lavender.
There are also small cicades jumping on the leaves by insects carrying microbacteria; into very dry weather they become very many."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is very popular in perfumery and cosmetics.
Eric Shes says, "Instead of very long ears with many large colors, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened, or absent altogether.
So we have fewer parts containing ether oil."
The solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more drought-resistant varieties.
