Her photographs in prison were unavailable, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, on which Manning in platinum shade wig, clearly feeling awkward, sits at the wheel of the car; with this photograph, she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey Harborg successfully completed his 2012 "Vision of Strangers".
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," explained Dewey-Hagborg at a preliminary screening of a new press exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her prison muse became correspondence friends and exchanged several letters over two years.
They even wrote a comic book of "Depressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, who depicted how in the future the president would ease Chelsea's punishment and she would be able to visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama really decided to free Manning just a few days after the book was released was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There is something deep and strong about the exhibition opening right now, when Donald Trump declares war on people who reveal secret information in the government, and invents new ways to incite on Twitter animosity that he is meant to soften.
When Dewey Harbor was asked about the coincidence of all of this over time, she said, "There's no such thing as an accident."
In an artist's statement written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature below (with a heart instead of a point over "i" in her name) calls for an end to "automated separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of penciled C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist is scientifically elegantly expressed), Dewey Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we are, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how much genetic data are open for interpretation and how subjective it is," Dewey Harbor said; her 2007 video work, False Memories, is also displayed here.
"DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of an exhibition that fits in one room is the above-mentioned novel in comic books.
It features King Kong-style Manning over the U.S. Correctional Casar building with a loudspeaker in hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," it says.
"So don't ever shut up."
"It's a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me," says the artist welcoming us from Philadelphia.
"I still get goose bumps when I talk about it."
Manning hasn't seen the exhibition in person - as it was visionaryally depicted in comic books - but when she comes, she will be greeted by masks in the middle of the room, her own genomic simulacs gathered like crowds of protesters.
It's also done intentionally, like everyone at the exhibition up to height (5"2, Manning's height), where the pencil painted genetic haplogroups.
"I'd hang them on walls earlier, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey Harbor says about portraits.
"I wanted them to look like a mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like a movement that stood behind her release."
