Startups that will help your company not to become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among his startup staff in electronic commerce, but the polls did not work.
Answers were often vague, useless, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees didn't trust the process.
"He was never consistent and objective," Herrett told the manager of a 75-man company in San Francisco, Madison Reed, engaged in e-commerce in hair care.
She therefore sought the assistance of third parties.
A new type of staff startup is now emerging, which helps companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software whose purpose is to measure staff involvement, they allow companies to make rapid inquiries, to contact certain teams and demographic groups, to offer staff anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases to allow informants to pass the top management and to contact the office directly.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup from Redwood City, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Herrett told me that she had reached a better understanding of what her staff thought and felt in three years of use of "Glint".
In addition to express interviews and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers the company's thermal map and shows in visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are slightly aware that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber involved in a scandal when a former employee published a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
The Internet portal Let's Talk About Pay, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation, and conformity industry may cost over $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Convercent startup from Denver, Colorado, helping companies to prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year against the backdrop of a fall in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has recently emerged among clients.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send individually commissioned staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report misconduct.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go straight to the board.
"Court of public opinion intercepted power from inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company is found to be ill-treated by employees or to behave unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, staff outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan reported.
"Ruby Tuesday", a chain of restaurants with over 25,000 employees working in 500 establishments, used Convercent for over a year to make sure that employees were aware of the rules and procedures, and to offer a simple way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if a staff member wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for a telephone number or a head office email, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
Often it was a frightening and awkward experience, reported James Vitrano, the chief of law at Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to track staff complaints.
Now that the company uses the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment, and unfair pay – can be quickly discovered and dealt with.
"I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of staff situation," Vitrano said, who runs the "Ruby Tuesday" network risk management team.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with staff".
According to Queensland, companies began to take staff ethics, values and involvement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed due to ethical irregularities as a result of Del Enron.
But it was only when the social media became widespread that the companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from viral distribution on the network.
"Before beginning to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly for the use of their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has been endorsed by venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received funding of $10 million from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from the Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The increasing volume of research shows that today's employees expect more from their jobs than before.
In hard-to-competition markets such as the Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, that is just the minimum.
Staff members want to feel that they are accepted and valued and that they devote their time to companies with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work with the company, they feel they are heard, and that the work they do results, they try more to make such a company a success," says Nina McQueen, vice president for global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when companies' portfolio business goes well; companies' business goes well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase staff loyalty and involvement, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to workplace cultural experts, it is important to have data on staff involvement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks staff for feedback, it may give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not take place quickly enough, or at all, disappointment may develop, and staff will lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be ready to have 4,000 interviews," says Russell Rat, president of the management consulting firm Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will wonder, "Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Herrett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly staff interviews, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem with "Glint".
And, after collecting feedback from staff dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday acquires new knowledge of its employees and hopes that in the long run this knowledge will help it to better retain staff in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you'll lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose company.
