Create a comic book novel: One castle in English History
In the recent past, Scottney's tiny castle was shot in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 1980s served as a shelter for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the Buhl River Valley in Kent County, he watched a turbulent story around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a smoked hair and a propensity for historical documents, for a comic book novel.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
The Castle in England covers a period from the Middle Ages to the Ewardian era and tells of families who lived in Scotland; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists, Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man's Teeth and Other Stories, a compilation of British Library documents; this project suddenly touched him to the bottom of his soul.
"I could just be touched by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because at those times the lights were on.
And in 300 years, in the future, you think you're there, too.
Oh, how I love archives!"
For a man caught in this passion for old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Art Council and living in the castle for four months ("I'm a little bit stuck there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle all day, walked through the archives, and considered numerous treasures of the estate and old things - such as the heads of hyenas on walls or bottles that had been in the ditch for centuries.
He was walking around the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to rangers, gardeners, and sometimes with artists working on illustrations of his book.
Then at night, he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Scotland Castle is not very well studied, because the National Foundation did not gain full access to it until 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassie, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the employees were just beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as "that the aristocrats have gone to the attic for centuries."
Diary, British Empire letters, maps showing who owned what, "You think land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but this bereza was fought by two families.
It happens like this, guys!"
In some of the compilation's stories, the castle becomes the starting point for broader explorations in English history: e.g. at the Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is evidence of a riot that occurred at the castle in 1380, in a book called the Knights Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes says.
"The Bristian uprising started in these places, and I thought the riot was a good start.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are strongly linked to the history of the castle, such as the Priest, which tells of the Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family has been hiding for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Contrabandist", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoned the coffin (it was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family of all who inhabited Scottie: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect con artist, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I imagine them as a company of handsome men who can care for the heirs of great fortunes."
After completing his job at Castle, Rhodes is looking for other possibilities to get a unique writing experience.
He lived two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamyanmäki, a place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it grew back into forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: damn it, I have to go back to real life again."
