Andrei Ochatkov was thrown from the cosmodrome.
As IA has become known, the technical director of the East Andrei Oslamkov Cosmodrome has begun to work at the Khrunishev State Space Production Centre (HCNC).
He had previously been de facto involved in the construction of the East Cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the management of the Land and Space Infrastructure Operations Centre (CENCI), he had been transferred to a plant in the Moscow Philosophies, where he would coordinate production.
Mr. Ochatkov will not have a replacement: the position of technical director is likely to be abolished, and the function is dispersed to the units of the CENCI.
That the technical director of the Eastern and Deputy Director-General for Technological Development of the CENCI, Andrei Oslamkov, had moved to work at the Hrunishev GCN, IA told top managers of several space industries, as well as a government official.
"He's been working in a new post for weeks," said the "I" interlocutors in the industry.
It was not possible to get the CENTI's operational comment on Thursday, and Mr. Oslamkov himself was not available for comment.
However, I've officially confirmed the information to HKNPC.
He decided to move to the position of Director of Production Coordination, stated at the plant. - Andrei Oslamkov has fully fulfilled his mission to provide a launch minimum for the first launch at the East Cosmodrome.
Mr. Ochatkov went to work at the CENCI in 2013, having served behind his back in space forces, particularly in Baikonur, and in Plesetsk, he served as the first deputy commander in the rank of colonel at the “north” cosmodrome.
In 2009, Andrei Oslamkov became a criminal subject.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly from his application, regional traders were paid for the backs of State orders, but failed to comply with the obligations undertaken to clean separated parts of the carrier rockets in the Arangela region and the Republic of Komi.
In 2012, the jury found him innocent.
Its technological development responsibilities in the CENCI have been extended to various projects, but the construction of the Far East Cosmodrome has been the main one.
The head of the then Federal Space Agency, Oleg Ostupenko, in an interview with IA, explicitly said that the state of affairs in East "was critical as early as October 2013".
The fact is that the planning was a strategic error: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned for the same time, at the end of 2015.
In order to launch before the end of the year, the construction was decided six months earlier and the dates were changed from December to July 2015.
In order to speed up the process, it had to be a trick: CENCI specialists had begun to install technology equipment in unbuilt facilities in parallel.
The main proponent of this idea was Andrei Oslamkov.
Despite the risks that existed and the transfer did occur (instead of December 2015 the Soyuz did not leave until April 28, 2016), this idea was justified, says the source "I" on the cosmodrome: "We would not have made a single launch with the East until now, but we would have been building."
Vice Premier Dmitri Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Oslamkov his "space Susanin", but he was the one who almost always requested information about the construction's progress.
Mr. Ochatkov remembered and was straightforward: for example, in an interview with IA, he suggested that the Federal Special Construction Agency (Spexstra) should be stripped of its status as the only performer in East and work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of Special Construction?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, the CENCI has assumed the duties of the general contractor to complete construction and installation work at the start-up and technical complex by the scheduled launches in the fourth quarter.
According to IA, Mr. Ochatkov's transition to a new job was motivated by disagreements with the management of the CENCI on how to complete the construction of the facilities and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as on how to work with subcontracted organizations.
"It was decided that it would be best for everyone," says one of the top managers involved in the construction of the East.
A government official, in turn, calls the solution strange: "He was one of the best professionals, it will be difficult to find an equivalent replacement for him."
According to IA, this will not be required: the post of technical director of the launch site will be abolished and its functions will be dispersed to the units of the CENCI.
