Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help alleviate the problem.
Red meat and chocolate are commonly regarded as a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, leads to colics and abdominal swelling, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Normally, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of a triptofan protein contributes to the production of immune cells that increase bowel tolerance.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells in the bowels ensured that harmful germs coming in with food did not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of launching an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too badly disrupted towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in their intestines show increasing tolerance of cells.
And this bacteria needs a triptophane -- one of the building blocks of a protein -- to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a link between one type of bacteria, the Lactobacillos reuteri, which is part of the normal microbial of the bowel, and the development of a population of cells that foster tolerance.
The more triptophane was contained in the feeding of mice, the more these immune cells they had."
He suggested that the same would work for people: a combination of L. reuteri and a triptophane-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammable environment in the bowel.
Postdoc Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganovas, studying a variety of tolerant immune cells, found that one group of guinea mice had these cells, and another group that belonged to the same line but was held separately had none.
She suggested that the distinction could be caused by microbial intestinal intestinal intestinals - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of mouse intestinal cells was sequenced, and six types of bacteria present in mice with immune cells but missing in mice without them were discovered.
Mouses grown in sterile environments that did not have a good microbial and that did not develop this type of immune cell received L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then carried small portions of liquid - without bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells separated from mice.
The immune cells have become more tolerant cells.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of triptophane, known as indol-3-milk acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of triptophane in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 per cent, but when the level of triptophane was halved, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether triptophane by-products from L. reuteri contribute to the development of cells in humans in the same way as mice, but in humans suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in triptophane-related genes have been found.
She says, "We may need to strengthen the development of these cells, because these cells are the key to inflammatory processes on the inside of the intestines.
High levels of triptophane with L. reuteri are potentially likely to increase their population."
