The disabled Anton Mamayev was fined.
Moshorsud reduced the sentence of the wheelchair disabled Anton Mamayev from four and a half years' imprisonment to a fine of 200,000 rubles.
The convicted person had previously been released from the SIZO by decision of the Timiryazevsk Court.
However, Moshorsud confirmed that the accused was a criminal because he organized the robbery and abduction of a scooter from a former SWAT fighter.
Moshorsud reduced Anton Mamayev's sentence to 200,000 rubles by his decision.
"Mamayev is the organizer of the robbery, which also forms part of the crime, and therefore such a person must be held criminally liable," explained IA spokesperson Moshorsud Ulyan Solopov.
In the present case, the court took account of Mamaev ' s state of health, the factual circumstances of the case, and the absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied article 64 of the Criminal Code, according to which punishment may be imposed below the lower limit.
With regard to Mamaev's assistant, Vasily Seroshtanov, the court did not establish the circumstances that would have led to a change in the category of gravity of the act and a change in the sentence.
Anton Mamayev himself stated that he remained unhappy with Moshorsud's decision.
I'm disappointed in the court's decision.
The only legitimate solution would be to justify it, and will continue to fight for justice.
His lawyer, Andrei Orlov, did not exclude appeals against the judgement before the Court of Cassation of Mosgorsud and the Supreme Court.
"We will use all the leverage up to the European Court of Human Rights," he said, "RIA News."
Remember, 28-year-old Moscow Anton Mamayev, suffering from spinal muscle atrophy, became a figure in the criminal case last fall.
The disabled claims to have bought a motorbike from acquaintances for 160,000 rubles to sell.
However, the scooter owners, among them a former SWAT fighter, claimed that the disabled and his assistant, Vasily Seroshtanov, had taken their property, threatening to use violence.
On 30 June, the Timiryazevsky District Court of Moscow sentenced Vasilia Seroshtanov to three years in the colony and Anton Mamayev to four and a half years ' imprisonment with serving his sentence in the general-regime colony (under article 162, paragraph 2, of the Criminal Code).
After the disabled person was placed in the SIZO, the Public Chamber, the Office of the Procurator-General for Human Rights under President Tatiana Moskalkov, joined the case.
As a result, in mid-July Anton Mamayev was released from SIZO by a decision of the same Timyrazev court.
The defence, in turn, appealed the decision of first instance in Mosgorsud.
