The White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the records of the armed forces provided by the magazine "TIME", the White House's decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers an entire $24,000.
White-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, became a central element of an event held on July 17 at the White House that featured American construction programmes.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials examined technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter produced in Connecticut was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire vehicle from Wisconsin, and a cargo truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the helicopter control division, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of the "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure you knew because this is an unusual, widely publicized event," wrote HMX-1 in an e-mail to his superior, the first deputy chief of Marine Corps aviation, the day before the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at around 7 a.m. on 17 July to participate in an event scheduled for 3 a.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to fly back in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security officers remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by TIME magazine, it is unclear whether a second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event contradicted this regulation.
"We asked, among other things, whether it was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that it wasn't," the commander wrote.
"You seem to have nowhere to go," the deputy chief replied.
The event "Delivered in America" was announced by the White House as an official event, and it was not covered by Hatch's law.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health-care reform then in the Senate and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to request them for the sake of photo ops.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessor.
"White house thrilled with the show "Make in America" featuring products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said White House's deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the United States President's transportation to the White House to the nearest inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to one official, the flight, performed for the event "Make in America", was counted to the crew for the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of "non-presidential support tasks".
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not been involved in organizing a helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not record the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's reimbursement rate for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records show that the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield at the Quantico Marine Air Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
"It is totally wrong to calculate the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement," Walters says.
"These approximate rates include personnel, service and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual allotments".
According to a 2015 study conducted by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do indeed take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House spokesperson Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of the helicopter's use for the event.
"The idea is to demonstrate this week things done in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose job depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we're all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
So, of course, it is perfectly appropriate to pay attention to this."
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking to the press about his own product fleet of the company.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said. "I have three."
