Electricity is cheaper for both residents and producers of Buryatia
The decades-long efforts of the Soviet and post-Soviet authorities of the Republic of Buryatia (East Siberia) to establish fair tariffs for electricity consumers are beginning to bear fruit.
Since 1 September, the cost of low voltage electricity for industrial recipients has been reduced by 25 per cent.
The Federal Antimonopoly Service of the Russian Federation, in accordance with the Resolution of the Government of the Russian Federation on amendments to the Regulations on the Wholesale Market for Electricity and Power and on the Consolidated Projected Balance of Production and Supply of Electrical Energy (power) within the Russian Single Energy System for the Entities of the Russian Federation (No. 842), established indicative electricity and power prices for industrial consumers of the Republic of Buryat.
As a result, the cost of electricity for buryats is reduced by a quarter, which will greatly facilitate the lives of small and medium-sized enterprises and individual entrepreneurs.
For many decades, the leaders of the Republic have been ploughing the threshold of Moscow's cabinets in futile attempts to equalize the region in tariffs with the neighbouring Irkut region with the hydropower cascade on Angara, flowing from Baikal, for which Buryatia is the main catchment area.
It was not until this year that changes began.
In March, electricity tariffs for the population of the Republic were reduced from 4.24 roubles/kWh to 3.93 roubles/kWh, or 7.3 per cent.
With the inclusion of Buryatiya by decision of the Federal Government in the List of Wholesale Price Zones for which the characteristics of wholesale and retail markets are established, industrial consumers have taken a turn.
According to analysts, this is only the beginning, as the population of the Irkutsk region pays for kilowatt/h 1.01 rubles.
But no one dares to name at least an approximate date for new tariff movements downwards for Buryatia.
