There will be two new territories in Russia that are leading socio-economic development, Abaza and Novotroitsk.
The relevant decisions of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and types of economic activity of the ToR in the territory of the city of Abaza in the Republic of Hakasia have been defined.
The city of 15,000 people will have a special legal regime for business activities, as well as a minimum capital investment by residents and a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to attract about 2.5 billion rubles of investment to the city, as well as to generate more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which Abaza will have a special legal regime for business activities, for example, includes crop production, animal husbandry, food production, non-alcoholic beverages and clothing.
Already, the Government has signed framework agreements for the implementation of eight investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the Territory's dependence on the Abaka Mine Towning Company.
In January 2017, the region's authorities reported that Hakasia had met all the conditions of Mineconom Development to create a TOR.
The authorities of the Orenburg region also did the same.
There, in the city of Novotroitsk, a territory that is leading socio-economic development will also be established.
This will lead to the diversification of the monocity economy, reduce its dependence on the urbanizing enterprise AO Ural steel, and create more than 23,000 jobs and attract investment of more than 8 billion rubles.
The list of economic activities in which the new TOR will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes, inter alia, freshwater fisheries, feed, medicines and medical supplies.
Novotrotitzk was the first of the monocitys of the Orenburg region to acquire the status of TOR.
It should be recalled that the area of advanced development is an economic zone with preferential tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
Among the benefits for the residents of the TOR are: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent in the first five years, and at least 10 per cent in the next five years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent in 10 years, the use of a free customs area, preferential access to various infrastructure facilities, and preferential rent rates.
